1Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a Simple View
Q1. Create a view named EmployeeView showing emp_id, name, and salary from Employees.
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW EmployeeView AS
SELECT emp_id, name, salary
FROM Employees;
2Ô∏è‚É£ Selecting from a View
Q2. Display all records from the EmployeeView.
Answer
sql
SELECT * FROM EmployeeView;
3Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a View with WHERE condition
Q3. Create a view HighSalaryEmp that shows employees with salary > 50000.
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW HighSalaryEmp AS
SELECT emp_id, name, salary
FROM Employees
WHERE salary > 50000;
4Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a View with JOIN
Q4. Create a view OrderDetailsView showing customer name and order amount.
Assume tables: Customers(customer_id, name) and Orders(order_id, customer_id, amount)
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW OrderDetailsView AS
SELECT c.name AS customer_name, o.amount
FROM Customers c
JOIN Orders o ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;
5Ô∏è‚É£ Updating a View (Updatable View)
Q5. Update salary using a view (EmployeeView).
Answer
sql
UPDATE EmployeeView
SET salary = 60000
WHERE emp_id = 101;
(Works only if view is simple and updatable.)

6Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a View with Aggregation
Q6. Create a view showing each department‚Äôs average salary.
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW DeptAvgSalary AS
SELECT department_id, AVG(salary) AS avg_salary
FROM Employees
GROUP BY department_id;
7Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a View with DISTINCT
Q7. Create a view showing unique job titles.
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW UniqueJobTitles AS
SELECT DISTINCT job_title
FROM Employees;
8Ô∏è‚É£ Replacing an Existing View
Q8. Modify EmployeeView to include department_id also.
Answer
sql
CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW EmployeeView AS
SELECT emp_id, name, salary, department_id
FROM Employees;
(MySQL, PostgreSQL support this; SQL Server uses ALTER VIEW)

9Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a Read-Only View
Q9. Create a view that cannot be updated.
Answer
sql
CREATE VIEW ReadOnlyEmployees AS
SELECT emp_id, name, salary
FROM Employees
WITH CHECK OPTION;
üîü Dropping a View
Q10. Drop the view named HighSalaryEmp.
Answer
sql
DROP VIEW HighSalaryEmp;
